        <body>
            <div1 n="2" rendition="#printed">
                <head>Why zines work</head>
                <list>
                    <item>
                        <emph>What is a zine ?</emph>
                        <p>A zine is a booklet <lb/>made by a transgender <lb/>anarchist who doesn't
                            have <lb/>any other options. <lb/>The Zine is a format <lb/>that's good
                            at containing <lb/>information. <lb/>A zine is a unit, a thing, <lb/>a
                            piece of information. <lb/>A zine is, specifically, <lb/>a
                                <emph>chunk</emph> of information. <lb/>It is made of + 7 smaller
                            <lb/>chunks of information.</p>
                        <p>A page folded thrice makes <lb/>for eight portions; six <lb/>smaller
                            pages and cover : <lb/>this is the classic format.</p>
                    </item>
                </list>
            </div1>
            <div1 n="2" rendition="#printed">
                <list>
                    <item><emph>WHen Doesn't it Work ?</emph>
                        <p>My last issue was a moment's <lb/>musing about pet play. <lb/>People
                            liked it! My previous <lb/>was about a much more <lb/>interesting topic
                            I've been <lb/>researching for a long time, <lb/>and nobody cared.
                                *<anchor xml:id="footnote1"/></p>
                        <!-- I used xml:id to create a locator for the footnote, I don't remember why
                        I did that and how I found that.-->
                        <p>Why did one work, and the <lb/>other didn't ? I think it was <lb/>the
                            format. <lb/>I broke the format with the <lb/>flop : it was a double
                            issue. <lb/>Double was too much ! Even I <lb/>got bored in the middle.
                            <lb/>I should have listened to
                                <lb/><persName><surname>Miller</surname></persName> and his famous
                            laws.</p>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <trailer> * <ptr target="#footnote1"/>
                    <objectName>#89 Puppygirl &amp; Philosopher</objectName> &amp; <objectName>#87
                        Synagogue Zodiac Mosaic</objectName>
                    <!-- I improvised something to link footnotes and their place in the text-->
                </trailer>
            </div1>
            <div1 n="3" rendition="#printed">
                <list>
                    <item>
                        <emph>The Law of Exactly Sevenish</emph>
                        <p>Seven has been a number of <lb/>magical and cosmic signifiance <lb/>for
                            all of human history. <lb/>Especially 1956. That's when <lb/><persName
                                ref="#Miller">George Miller</persName> wrote
                                    <lb/><emph><objectName>The Magical Number 7,
                                +2</objectName></emph>. <lb/>The paper exemplains why you can
                            <lb/>remember a telephone number <lb/>but not a credit card number.</p>
                        <p>I think <persName ref="#Miller">Miller</persName>'s Law is about more
                            than just human short<caesura/>term memory. What if it applies not to
                            just our brains, but information itself ? What if it's part of a
                                <emph>general information theory</emph> that we don't have yet
                            ?Regardless, it applies to zines.</p>
                    </item>
                </list>
            </div1>
            <div1 n="4" rendition="#printed">
                <list>
                    <item><emph>The Theory of Memes</emph>
                        <p>Before it was rare Soyjaks, <emph>the meme was a serious theory by
                                    <persName ref="#Dawkins">Dawkins</persName> '76. He named
                                memetics following genetics, including select<caesura/>tion. But his
                                evolutionary metaphor didn't even apply to evolution. Don't get me
                                wrong, I like his theory (and evolution.) But <persName
                                    ref="#Dawkins">Dawkins</persName> called a meme a unit of
                                culture. Sounds squishy, doesn't it ? Let's call it instead <emph>a
                                    chunk of information.</emph> Even better, a
                                    <emph>mirrorable</emph> chunk of information : one that can be
                                easily repeated. </emph>.</p>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <trailer>For us, by Xerox.</trailer>
            </div1>
            <div1 n="5" rendition="#printed">
                <list>
                    <item><emph>The Mirroring Section</emph>
                        <p>I guess that makes this the mirroring section. The mirroring Section. You
                            may have heard of <emph>mirror neurons</emph>
                            <caesura/> they're a useful discovery that's become something of a meme
                            !</p>This is the <emph>monkey see; do</emph> network in your brain. It
                        means that the Xerox in our brain is essential to learning and being : we
                        copy, we become. Likewise inform<caesura/>ation copies and becomes.<p/>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <trailer>So what does the mirror network mirror, anyway ? ... "Phenomena ?" I think
                    it deals in chunks.</trailer>
            </div1>
            <div1 n="6" rendition="#printed">
                <list>
                    <item><emph>Shrink To Grow</emph>
                        <p>Notice that you don't have to read <persName ref="#Miller"
                                >Miller</persName>
                            <persName ref="#Dawkins">Dawkins</persName> and ... uh, <persName
                                ref="#Rizzolatti">Rizzolatti</persName> to follow me. That's because
                            their books compress into my mini-page chunks. The behavior of the
                            chunkd is what mattered to <persName ref="#Miller">Miller</persName>,
                            not the number. They <emph>compress, nest, and scale.</emph></p>
                        <p>Scaling means that the <emph>riot <choice>
                                    <orig>grrl</orig>
                                    <corr>girl</corr>
                                </choice></emph> concept can go from zine idea to cultural Thing. If
                            copied and shared, the information you're reading could
                            compress-nest-scale, too. It would no longer be 6 chunks about
                                        <emph><persName ref="#Miller">Miller</persName>,
                                mirroring, and memetics.</emph> It would become one idea, a Zine
                            Theory, told in one word: <emph>zinetics.</emph></p>
                    </item>
                </list>
            </div1>
